[[File:Beaver dam partially blown out at fish ladder at Jalama Weir below U. S. Highway 1 2014-04.jpg|thumb|Beaver dam partially blown out by winter rains at trout fish ladder on Salsipuedes Creek below Hwy 1 at Jalama Weir.]]

'''Salsipuedes Creek''' is a {{convert|9.9|mi|km}} long stream,<ref name=nhd>{{cite web |title= The National Map |publisher= United States Geological Survey |url=http://viewer.nationalmap.gov/viewer |accessdate=2014-05-01 }}</ref> flowing north to join the [[Santa Ynez River]] just southeast of [[Lompoc, California|Lompoc]] in [[Santa Barbara County, California]]. Salsipuedes Creek, along with its major tributary, El Jaro Creek,<ref>{{cite gnis|241894|El Jaro Creek}}</ref> is the largest tributary to the lower Santa Ynez River, shortly before the river reaches the [[Pacific Ocean]].

==History==
The river was first named by the Spanish '''Arollo del Jaro'''.<ref name=Gudde/> In the Spanish language it means "get out if you can", a name conferred on flashy streams in narrow canyons.

==Watershed and Course==
The Salsipuedes Creek/El Jaro Creek watershed drains approximately {{convert|47.1|sqmi|sqkm}} and flows roughly {{convert|25.1|mi|km}} from its headwaters along the coastal [[Santa Ynez Mountains]] to its confluence with the lower Santa Ynez River.<ref>{{cite report |title=Jalama Weir/Salsipuedes Creek Fish Ladder Wooden Structure Removal â€“ Cachuma Project Final Environmental Assessment |publisher=U. S. Department of Interior Bureau of Reclamation |date=January 2011|url=http://www.usbr.gov/mp/nepa/documentShow.cfm?Doc_ID=7198 |accessdate=2014-05-01 }}</ref>

Salsipuedes Creek runs north from its source along Jalama Road until it is met by El Jaro Creek, a 13-mile long tributary, just south of where Jalama Road meets [[U.S. Highway 1]], then Salsipuedes Creek mainstem continues north along Highway 1 to Santa Rosa Road, where the creek has its confluence with the Santa Ynez River. El Jaro Creek has two tributaries with intermittent flows, Los Amoles Creek and Ytias Creek, which are {{convert|3.5|mi|km}} and {{convert|4.2|mi|km}} long, respectively.<ref name=CEMAR>{{cite report |title=Steelhead/rainbow trout resources of Santa Barbara County |authors=Gordon Becker, Andrew Gunther |year= |publisher=Center for Ecosystem Management and Restoration (CEMAR) |url=http://www.cemar.org/SSRP/pdfs/SSRP_santaBarbara.pdf |accessdate=2014-05-01 }}</ref>

==Ecology==
Upper Salsipuedes Creek and El Jaro Creeks have perennial flows and provide good [[steelhead trout]] (''Oncorhynchus mykiss'') habitat.<ref name=CEMAR/> Southern steelhead trout were listed as [[endangered species|endangered]] in 1997, when the [[National Marine Fisheries Service]] listed the [[anadromous]] trout below Bradbury Dam on the Santa Ynez River as critical habitat under the [[Endangered Species Act]] of 1973. [[North American beaver]] (''Castor canadensis'') improve juvenile rearing habitat for salmonids and are prevalent on Salsipuedes Creek, coincidentally the best trout habitat in the Santa Ynez River watershed.

